One assignment I found really valuable was Problem Set 4. It helped me understand how to build and use a thermal resistance network to analyze heat transfer problems.
Before this assignment, I mostly focused on plugging numbers into equations, but drawing the resistance network helped me visualize how heat actually moves through each layer of the system. 
Breaking the problem into different resistances made it much easier to organize the equations and understand why each one was being used. 
This assignment also helped me think more about whether my answers made sense in a real-world context. 
Instead of just trusting the math, I started asking myself what kind of values I should expect and whether my result seemed reasonable. 
That way of thinking helped me catch mistakes and better understand the physics behind the problem. 
I think this will be useful in future engineering work because it trains me to approach problems more logically and not just rely on calculations alone.
